WHILE relief efforts were under way after a blaze ripped through Masiphumelele in the early hours of Saturday leaving hundreds of residents displaced, firefighters on the other side of the mountain were fighting a vegetation fire near Hospital Bend. The City’s traffic spokesperson Richard Coleman explained that the slip way onto Philip Kgosana Drive as well as the quarry behind Hudson Street, were closed at Hospital Bend while firefighters brought the blaze under control. The City of Cape Town’s fire and rescue services spokesperson Jermaine Carelse they were alerted to the Masiphumelele fire at about 1.23am on Saturday. At least 15 firefighting appliances from various fire stations, and 50 firefighters extinguished the blaze by 7.24am. No injuries or fatalities were reported. Charlotte Powell, the City of Cape Town’s Disaster Risk Management Centre’s spokesperson, said the blaze destroyed 100 structures leaving 235 people homeless. “The Gift of the Givers is providing humanitarian assistance. Various city departments are on site and assisting the affected community,” she said. The Gift of the Givers’ Dr Imtiaz Sooliman, said the organisation was contacted by Cape Town disaster management for assistance for the desperate community, following the fire. “Gift of the Givers’ teams are preparing hot nutritious meals, which will be delivered at noon. These will be accompanied by bottled water, blankets and baby-care packs as an initial intervention. Our vehicles are packed and ready. “Gift of the Givers has also assisted communities at Masiphumelele on previous occasions,” Powell said.